\begin{theorem}[Existence of an Albanese variety uniformly over the marked point]
  \label{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.nonempty_jacobianWitness}
  \uses{def:IsAlbanese, def:Jacobian, def:genus}
  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. There exists a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ of relative dimension $g(C)$ such that, for every $k$-rational point $P \in C(k)$, the scheme $J$ is an Albanese object for the pointed curve $(C, P)$ in the sense of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:IsAlbanese}
  The underlying scheme $J$ depends only on $C$, not on the choice of marked point; only the universal morphism $\iota_P \colon C \to J$ varies with $P$. Two classical constructions provide $J$:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item $g(C) \ge 1$: (i) take $J = \Pic^0_{C/k}$, the connected component of the identity of the Picard scheme; for every $P \in C(k)$, the Abel--Jacobi map $\iota_P \colon C \to \Pic^0_{C/k}$, $Q \mapsto [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)]$, sends $P$ to the identity and satisfies the universal property by the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$. Equivalently, (ii) form the Stein factorisation of $\Sym^g(C) \to \Pic^g_{C/k}$ translated by $-gP$. Both routes yield a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme of dimension $g(C)$.
    \item $g(C) = 0$: take $J = \Spec k$, the trivial $k$-group scheme of dimension $0$. The Albanese universal property in this case reduces to the rigidity assertion that every morphism $f \colon C \to A$ from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve $C$ to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ with $f(P) = \eta_A$ is the constant morphism at $\eta_A$. Classically, this follows from $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ together with the fact that a genus-$0$ curve with a $k$-rational point is isomorphic to $\mathbb P^1_k$ (Brauer--Severi). The unique morphism $\Spec k \to A$ then provides the required factorisation.
  \end{itemize}
  Mathlib currently contains neither Pic-scheme representability, nor symmetric powers / quotients of schemes by finite group actions, nor the rigidity theorem $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ for morphisms to abelian varieties. The existence statement is therefore recorded here as a single working hypothesis backing all downstream consequences (the four protected instances on $\Jac(C)$, the Abel--Jacobi map and its universal property of Chapter~\ref{chap:AbelJacobi}). Both the higher-genus existence and the genus-$0$ rigidity content are encapsulated in this single hypothesis.
\end{proof}

